<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO SW</font><br>
<tt>Fri Sep 19 12:35:35 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
SW: After 25 years of being an &quot;active&quot; shrink I pulled back. I noticed that I was losing my edge, my ability to detach and care, my empathy. Doing therapy to me was like painting is to an artist, it was my art. To help others think and feel their way to a better life was the most rewarding thing I knew how to do.  The worst thing I could imagine was becoming a hack, a lifer, a non caring person going through the motions.<br><br>
Yes, I have seen and heard it all, but no, I personally have not had PTSD or anything similiar. I have had my share of depressions, other reactions, had patients die, get worse, get better, and stay the same.  Yeah,  I carry a bit of all of them in me.  When I am &quot;up&quot; I remember the triumphs, when I am down, I remember the bad ones, like the 16 year old girl who slashed her wrists in my waiting room,<br>
or the Police Officer I drank beer with at 2 AM on a pier, as he adjusted to the fact that his wife and her parents had just been murdered in a stop and rob. Or those that sucked their guns, and those that didn't.  It is really amazing when I look at the rows of files in my office, how many lives are filed away in their. Stories that bridge probably every human experience.  I guess I was the ultimate voyeur to most of it.<br><br>
Most of counseling is more mundane, marital problems, parent child problems, self image stuff, and a therapist is expected to care.  It becomes like watching soap operas on TV, every hour you change channels and plug into another life.  That's when I knew I had to pull back. I had burned out.  When someone's pain is so intense that they are in tears telling you, and you can't stop wiping your own eyes, you have lost that &quot;clinical detachment&quot; wall you are expected to have.  I lost or gave mine away long ago.<br><br>
After all those years of hearing all the other feelings, this site let me express what was inside me. From not going to war to re evaluating my thinking, and feelings, on Vietnamese people.  This site is safe, as I am sure you all know. And like Chet, I too am now wondering who I am and where I am going. I know where I was, and that I can't do that anymore, not with the same degree of honesty and perfection that I demand of myself.  Now I am wandering and searching, reevaluating my past and future.  I don't know, SW if that answers all your questions, but its all I can say right now. I guess I got something in my eye...<br><br>
doc
